NEW YORK (AP) ‚Äî Several mainstream Republican Senate candidates are drawing on the ‚Äúgreat replacement‚Äù conspiracy theory once confined to the far-right fringes of U.S. politics to court voters this campaign season, promoting the baseless notion that there is a plot to diminish the influence of white people in America.

In some cases, the comments have gone largely overlooked given the hard-line immigration rhetoric that has become commonplace among conservatives during the Trump era. But a weekend mass shooting in Buffalo, New York, that may have been inspired by the racist theory is drawing new attention to the GOP‚Äôs growing embrace of white nationalist creed.

Three weeks ago in Arizona, Republican Senate candidate Blake Masters accused Democrats of trying to flood the nation with millions of immigrants ‚Äúto change the demographics of our country.‚Äù A few days later in Missouri, Senate hopeful Eric Schmitt, the state attorney general, said Democrats were ‚Äúfundamentally trying to change this country through illegal immigration.‚Äù And in Ohio, Republican Senate nominee JD Vance accused Democrats of trying to ‚Äútransform the electorate.‚Äù

Warning of an immigrant ‚Äúinvasion,‚Äù Vance told Fox News Channel that Democrats ‚Äúhave decided that they can‚Äôt win reelection in 2022 unless they bring a large number of new voters to replace the voters that are already here.‚Äù

Some of the Republican campaigns denied that their statements amounted to replacement theory, but among the experts, there is little question.

Five experts on hate speech who reviewed the Republican candidates‚Äô comments confirmed that they promote the baseless racist theory, even though the Republicans don‚Äôt mention race directly.

Azovsteel finally evacuated - US admiral among the "evacuees"

The hotbed of resistance in the Azov steelworks, which had been fought over for weeks and consisted mainly of Azov troops and foreign mercenaries, has now been conquered by Russian and DPR troops. As was already known from other fighters who had been smuggled out of the factory beforehand, there were numerous foreign "mercenaries" providing military advice and fighting among those who persevered.

Surrender officially confirmed

In a video speech on Tuesday, Ukrainian President Zelenskyi effectively confirmed the surrender of the Ukrainian military at the Azov steel plant in Mariupol, without mentioning the word surrender.

According to the Azov commander in the steelworks, Denis Prokopenko, the following figures and statements are available:

20 seriously wounded, 31 relatively healthy surrendered in Azovstal.
One of the resistance groups capitulated and broke away from the main group.
They surrendered under the guarantee of their lives.
Nobody promised them an exchange.

This was also confirmed by reports from the Ukrainian news agency Ukrinform, in their reports.

Among other things, we had already reported on a Canadian general who had to surrender. Now, however, a highly decorated US Navy 4-star general has emerged among the last remaining.

US General and 'Silver Star' bearer among the 'prisoners'

Despite weeks of interventions by high-ranking and less influential (e.g. Austria's Chancellor Nehammer) European politicians to guarantee safe conduct for those trapped in Azov, the Russian leadership did not get involved in this "cow-bargain". Apparently in the knowledge of the high-ranking "Western military" who were on site.

Up to the end, the Ukrainian side (with the support of the West) had tried to obtain a ‚Äúprisoner exchange‚Äù with Russian soldiers. However, since there were no high-ranking members of the army among the prisoners taken by Ukraine, this ‚Äúattempt to cover it up‚Äù by the western infiltration also came to nothing.

The fighters who have now been captured are to be taken to the city of Novoazovsk in eastern Ukraine, controlled by DPR (Donetsk People's Republic) units, and given medical care there. Among them, as can be seen on the pictures of the "evacuees", Admiral Eric Thor Olson.
- - -
"Career" of US Special Forces "Emergency Responder"

Olson was born on January 24, 1952 in Tacoma Washington and was, among other things, a USN commander, Navy Seal instructor and recipient of the 'Silver Star'. He served from 1973 to 2011, most recently with the rank of 4-star Admiral.

In 1993 he was awarded the 'Silver Star' in the 'Battle of Mogadishu'. Olson was commander for "special operations" of the US, the so-called Warfare Development Group. The name alone reveals a lot about the intentions of his "employer".
